eland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Brampton, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Brampton, Suffolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Shadingfield, Suffolk, England":"Shadingfield, Suffolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 1356–":"about 1356–Deceased","1356–Male":"1356–Deceased","1366–Female":"1366–Deceased","1300–Male":"1300–Deceased","1325–1372":"1325–1372","1386–Male":"1386–Deceased","1492–Male":"1492–Deceased","1339–Male":"1339–Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","1385":"1385","abt 1492":"about 1492","1372":"1372","Abt 1356":"about 1356","1492":"1492","1325":"1325","1356":"1356","1300":"1300","1366":"1366","Abt 1386":"about 1386","1386":"1386","about 1356":"about 1356","1339":"1339","Suffolk County, England":"Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","Brampton, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Brampton, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","Shadingfield, Suffolk, England":"Shadingfield, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Duke","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: nickname from Middle English <i>duk(ke)</i>, <i>duck</i>, <i>doke</i>, <i>dook</i> ‘duck’ (Old English <i>dūce</i>), either from a perceived resemblance (perhaps a waddling gait) or from association with wild fowling. Compare   Duck  ,   Drake  .","English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Duk</i> or <i>Duke</i>. In northern England this is usually a pet form of <i>Marmaduke</i>. It may alternatively be a survival of one or more Old English personal names, though it is uncertain whether they were still current in the period of surname formation. Old English <i>Ducc(a)</i> is attested in placenames like Duxford (Cambridgeshire) and Duckington (Cheshire), and was perhaps interchangeable with <i>Docc</i>, attested in Doxey (Staffordshire) and Doxford (Northumberland). <i>Duke</i> could also represent Old English <i>Deowuc</i> (as in Deuxhill, Shropshire). A surname from <i>Marmaduke</i> is on record until at least 1881 and derives from the personal name <i>Marmaduke</i>, apparently an Anglo-Norman French pronunciation of Old Irish <i>Maolmaedóc</i> ‘devotee of <i>Maedóc</i>’; see   Duckett  .","Americanized form of Polish <b>Duk</b>: nickname from <i>dukać</i> ‘to stammer or falter’."],"variants":[{"name":"Dock","meanings":["English and Scottish: variant of   Duke  .","Norwegian: habitational name from a farm named Dokk, from Old Norse <i>dǫkk</i> ‘hollow, depression’.","North German (Lower Saxony): possibly a metonymic occupational name for someone who worked in the cloth trade, from Middle Low German <i>dōk</i> ‘fabric’."]},{"name":"Doke","meanings":["English: variant of   Duke  ."]},{"name":"Duch","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Vietnamese Nga, Phal, Phan, Sophan, Tha, Thang, Yen.  German Kurt, Klaus.","Polish, Sorbian, and Ukrainian: nickname from <i>duch</i> ‘spirit, breath’.","Czech: from a short form of the Old Czech personal name <i>Duchoslav</i>, composed of the elements <i>duch</i> ‘spirit’ + <i>slav</i> ‘glory’ or ‘famous’."]},{"name":"Duckett","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Yorkshire): from the Middle English personal name <i>Duket</i>. This may sometimes have been an early Middle English pet form of an Old English <i>Ducc(a)</i>, but was more often a pet form of <i>Marmaduke</i>, especially in Yorkshire (see   Duke  ). <i>Marmaduke</i> itself is from Irish <i>Maol Maedóc</i> ‘servant of Maedóc’, <i>Maedóc</i> being the name of prominent Irish saints of the 6th and 7th centuries."]},{"name":"Duck","meanings":["English: variant of   Duke  .","Irish: adoption of the English name (see 1 above) as an equivalent of <b>Lohan</b> (an Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Leocháin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Leochán</i>’) by mistranslation, as if from <i>lacha</i> ‘duck’.","North German (also <b>Dück</b>) and German (<b>Dück</b>): see   Dueck  ."]},{"name":"Dukes","meanings":["English: variant of   Duke  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]}]},{"name":"Roger","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name, <i>Rog(i)er</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, from <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>gār</i>, <i>gēr</i> ‘spear’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain, replacing the native Old English form <i>Hrōðgār</i>. <i>Roger</i> was one of the most popular boys' names throughout the medieval period, but less so after the Reformation, though it has continued in regular use to the present day.  Roger, Count of Sicily  (  <i>c.</i>1031–1101 ), son of Tancred, recovered Sicily from the Arabs. His son, also called Roger, ruled Sicily as king, presiding over a court noted for its splendour and patronage of the arts."],"variants":[{"name":"Rodger","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Roger  , in part from the surname derived from the given name in the Middle Ages."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Roger Duke was born about 1356, in Shadingfield, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom as the son of Walter Duke and Mrs. Duke. He married Mrs Roger Duke in 1385, in Brampton, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 3 sons and 1 daughter. He died in Suffolk, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"about 1356–":"umbes 1356–Surnud","1356–Male":"1356–Surnud","1366–Female":"1366–Surnud","1300–Male":"1300–Surnud","1325–1372":"1325–1372","1386–Male":"1386–Surnud","1492–Male":"1492–Surnud","1339–Male":"1339–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1385":"1385","abt 1492":"umbes 1492","1372":"1372","Abt 1356":"umbes 1356","1492":"1492","1325":"1325","1356":"1356","1300":"1300","1366":"1366","Abt 1386":"umbes 1386","1386":"1386","about 1356":"umbes 1356","1339":"1339","Suffolk County, England":"Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Brampton, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Brampton, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Shadingfield, Suffolk, England":"Shadingfield, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"abo